    "background": "Chebyshev's Rule and the Empirical Rule are useful as a check on the calculation of the standard deviation. For example, suppose we calculated the standard deviation for the R&D percentages (Table 2.8) to be 3.92. Are there any 'clues' in the data that enable us to judge whether this number is reasonable?",
    "data": "\\begin{tabular}{rrrrrrrrrr}\n\\hline Table 2.8 & \\multicolumn{10}{|l}{ R&D Percentages for 50 Companies } \\\\\n\\hline 13.5 & 9.5 & 8.2 & 6.5 & 8.4 & 8.1 & 6.9 & 7.5 & 10.5 & 13.5 \\\\\n72 & 7.1 & 9.0 & 9.9 & 8.2 & 13.2 & 9.2 & 6.9 & 9.6 & 77 \\\\\n9.7 & 7.5 & 7.2 & 5.9 & 6.6 & 11.1 & 8.8 & 5.2 & 10.6 & 8.2 \\\\\n11.3 & 5.6 & 10.1 & 8.0 & 8.5 & 11.7 & 7.1 & 7.7 & 9.4 & 6.0 \\\\\n8.0 & 7.4 & 10.5 & 7.8 & 79 & 6.5 & 6.9 & 6.5 & 6.8 & 9.5\n\\end{tabular}",
